# docs/specs/ — Feature and Component Specifications

This directory holds specifications that define requirements and interfaces
before implementation. Agents working from a spec treat it as the source
of truth for what to build.

**Important:** Files in this directory are agent work artifacts — agentify
never overwrites them. Only this README.md is maintained by agentify.

## How Agents Use This Directory

1. Find the relevant spec before implementing (or confirm one doesn't exist)
2. Read it completely — the spec defines the contract
3. Note ambiguities and ask for clarification before coding
4. Do not deviate from the spec without updating it first

## File Naming Convention

`feature-or-component-slug.md`

Examples: `oauth-provider.md`, `payment-webhook-api.md`, `user-auth-service.md`

## Spec File Format

```markdown
---
title: "Feature or component name"
status: draft | review | approved | implemented | deprecated
version: "1.0"
created: YYYY-MM-DD
updated: YYYY-MM-DD
---

## Overview

What this feature/component does and why it exists. (3-5 sentences)

## Requirements

### Functional

- REQ-001: (what the system must do)
- REQ-002: ...

### Non-Functional

- Performance: ...
- Security: ...
- Constraints: ...

## Interface / API

(Public interface — function signatures, REST endpoints, data structures,
config schema, CLI flags, etc.)

## Examples

(1-3 concrete usage examples showing inputs and expected outputs)

## Out of Scope

- Explicit list of what this spec does NOT cover
- Known limitations or deferred items

## Open Questions

- (Questions that must be answered before implementation can begin)
```

## Status Lifecycle

`draft` → `review` → `approved` → `implemented` (or `deprecated` if superseded)
